    </ol>
    <div class="carousel-inner">

      <div class="carousel-item active">
        <img class="igorot-img" src="Images/beach-filipinos.jpg" alt="">
        <div class="general-padding">
          <h3>Bontok</h3>
          <p>The Bontok were head-hunters and had distinctive tattoos. Head-hunters had chest tattoos called chak-lag, while regular people had tattoos on the arms and legs called pong-o. They believed in a hierarchy of anitos
            or spirits, Lumawid the highest among them. Bontok communities were called ato, which ranged from 14-50 houses. </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="carousel-item">
        <img class="igorot-img" src="Images/beach-filipinos.jpg" alt="">
        <div class="general-padding">
          <h3>Ibaloi</h3>
          <p>The Ibaloi was an agrarian society and continue their agricultural practices today. Their language is related to Pangasinan, a language spoken in the Pangasinan area of Luzon. They were known for throwing feasts
            for the community. The largest among them is called Pesshet, which is sponsored by the wealthy and food shared with all members. Pesshet would last for weeks during which the Ibaloi would sacrifice animals to appease the spirits.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="carousel-item">
        <img class="igorot-img" src="Images/beach-filipinos.jpg" alt="">
        <div class="general-padding">
          <h3>Ifugao</h3>
          <p>The Ifugao derived their names from Ipugo, meaning people of the earth or mortals, distinguishing themselves from spirits. The Ifugao are best known for creating the Banaue Rice Terraces. The Ifugao arranged their societal hierarchy by wealth with the kadangyan or the elite at the top, the tagu in the middle, and the nawotwot at the bottom. The elite throws feasts for the community called hagabi. They speak four dialects and are well-known for their oral traditions.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="carousel-item">
        <img class="igorot-img" src="Images/beach-filipinos.jpg" alt="">
        <div class="general-padding">
          <h3>Isneg</h3>
          <p>The word Isneg derives from Itneg or the people who live near the Tineg River. They are also known as the Apayao. They are thought to have originated from Southern China. They were a head-hunting society and threw feasts called say-am after a successful head-hunt. Labor was divided by sex with the men farming, building and hunting, and the women harvesting, gathering, cooking and crafting small tools. They speak Isneg and Ilongo.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="carousel-item">
        <img class="igorot-img" src="Images/beach-filipinos.jpg" alt="">
        <div class="general-padding">
          <h3>Kalinga</h3>
          <p>The Limos-Liwan Kalinga or Kalinga for short had settled the Southern and Northern Cordilerras Mountains. They heavily ornamented themselves with distinct tattoos and were known head-hunters. They practiced both wet and dry farming. Whang-Od, the oldest living Filipino traditional tattoo artist, is well known throughout the world. She is the last practitioner of botok or hand-tapping tattoos. Filipinos and non-Filipinos alike travel to the Kalinga province for her services.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="carousel-item">
        <img class="igorot-img" src="Images/beach-filipinos.jpg" alt="">
        <div class="general-padding">
          <h3>Kankanaey</h3>
          <p>Like the Ifugao they created sloping terraces and had similar housing styles. They were a primarily agrarian society. The Kankanaey separated their young bachelors into dap-ay, the men's dormitory, and the ebgan, the women's dormitory. There are two main dialects of Kankanaey: hard and soft speaking Kankanaey which differ in intonation. Hard and soft speakers also differ in the region they live and their cultural practices.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
